[...]"

dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: A fuzzer is available and is used.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: Runtime assertions are there. 'Many' is relative.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: Met with the TPM 2 emulation part. Possibly problematic with the TPM 1.2 emulation part that uses SHA-1.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: Integrated with Travis. Swtpm project uses libtpms and tests it as well.

name: ModSecurity
description: ModSecurity is an open source, cross platform web application firewall (WAF) engine for Apache, IIS and Nginx that is developed by Trustwave's SpiderLabs. With over 10,000 deployments world-wide, ModSecurity is the most widely deployed WAF in existence.

name: ONAP AAF (Application Authorization Framework)
description:
AAF is designed to cover Fine-Grained Authorization, meaning that the Authorizations provided are able to used an Applicationâ€™s detailed authorizations, such as whether a user may be on a particular page or has access to a particular Pub-SUB topic controlled within the App.

AAF's Client Framework, "CADI" provide multi-Authentication to a normalized identity, which is paired with Authorization to provide full validation of incoming transaction before processing.

These are critical functions for Cloud environments, as Services need to be able to be installed and running in a very short time, and should not be encumbered with local stores of User Password and/or Permissions.

report_process_justification: The description of the process can be found in the following URL: https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Tracking+Issues+with+JIRA
report_responses_justification: The reported issues are being handled as soon as possible.
enhancement_responses_justification: The reported issues are being handled as soon as possible.

test_invocation_justification: JUnits are also run as part of the Maven Build
tests_documented_added_justification: This is documented on our wiki: Code Coverage and Static Code Analysis
warnings_strict_justification: Build systems run the compile with test flag enabled by default. So any failure in test cases will fail the ci and the merge request.
crypto_published_justification: AAF's CADI Framework makes use of best use of Java's protocols/algorithms available.
crypto_call_justification: AAF does not reimplement Java Cryptography.
delivery_mitm_justification: HTTP/S is a requirement in interactions with AAF/between users of AAF.
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: Security Scans are regularly run.  There are no issues.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: All the projects use Java which are memory safe that run on JVM. Also the end product runs on a docker container which is run on docker.
crypto_weaknesses_justification: AAF's CADI Framework defaults usage of TLS 1.1+
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: For each pull request, the project needs to be built successfully before the Merge option becomes activated. The test will be run automatically during the building process as well. Once build successfully and all tests has past, the Merge option will be activated.
discussion_justification: A mailing list is used for project related discussion. New users could also check, search the old discussion online at onap-discuss website. Joining the ONAP Technical Community
english_justification: JIRA is used to track bugs. The whole website is in English. Tracking Issues with JIRA
hardening_justification: The project tries to use hardening mechanism whenever possible.  AAF (and CADI) log all secure transactions, with critical info, such as kind of Authentication, the ID, the IP , etc.
crypto_used_network_justification: AAF/CADI defaults all clients to HTTP/S TLS1.1 & TLS1.2 from the outset.
crypto_tls12_justification: AAF/CADI defaults all clients to HTTP/S TLS1.1 & TLS1.2 from the outset.
crypto_certificate_verification_justific: TLS processing is handled by Java
crypto_verification_private_justificatio: CADI Clients do not allow HTTP... only HTTP/S, and these are defaulted to TLS 1.1+
hardened_site_justification: // X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
installation_common_justification: Source is delivered as Java Jars.  Docker Containers are also generated, for use in either Docker Directly, or within Kubernetes.
dco_justification:
ONAP requires both a Developer Certificate of Origin (DCO), and a Contributor License Agreement (CLA).
https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Contribution+Agreements
governance_justification:
The project governance is described at
https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Community+Offices+and+Governance
Further information can be found at https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/ONAP+Technical+Community+Document
code_of_conduct_justification: ONAP adheres to the Linux Foundation Code of Conduct, found at https://lfprojects.org/policies/code-of-conduct
roles_responsibilities_justification:
The key roles in the project and their responsibilities are described at
https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Community+Offices+and+Governance
Current members are listed at
https://wiki.onap.org/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=8226539
access_continuity_justification:
We have 4 committers and multiple contributes who are listed in
https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Resources+and+Repositories#ResourcesandRepositories-ActiveandAvailableInventory
All 4 committers have access and rights to maintain the code base, approve and review incoming changes and release a new version of the artifact. This will let the project continue with minimal to no interruption if one person is incapacitated. 
Also this project is controlled by the linux foundation so we can add more committers if needed
bus_factor_justification:
All the projects covered in this report have more than 2 persons who actively contribute and maintain code. 
https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/q/project:aaf/authz
https://gerrit.onap.org/r/#/q/project:aaf/cadi
documentation_quick_start_justification:
Information on setting up ONAP can be found at 
https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/guides/onap-develo:per/settingup/index.html
AAF Specific info
https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/aaf/authz.git/docs/sections/installation/index.html
https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/aaf/authz.git/docs/sections/configuration/index.html
documentation_current_justification: Documentation is updated with each release (using readthedocs.io strategy)
documentation_achievements_justification: The badge is visible on the project's readme.io page found at https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/aaf/authz.git/docs/index.html
accessibility_best_practices_justificati: Most of AAF is Service Based.  Colors for Management GUI were chosen by ONAP Standards for readability.  Standards for Field identification are followed, for instance, "Required" are not just red, but have Asterix'
internationalization_justification: Most of AAF is Service Based, and text entered is user defined.  It is, however, designed primarily for Developers/IT Professionals, so English (as instructed) is first language of logging, etc.
sites_password_security_justification: AAF Tool is intended to delegate User/Password to the Organization.  When this is not available, however, AAF stores as salted-SHA256 Hashes.  Certificate Authentication (Provided) is promoted above any use of User/Password.
maintenance_or_update_justification: All major releases are tagged in gerrit and the artifacts are stored with the release information on onap.nexus. So we can access all old versions of the artifact. If and when a upgrade requires certain steps to be followed they are being added to the release documents as needed
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio:
Vulnerabilities can be reported using the link
https://wiki.onap.org/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=6591711
Currently we dont have any vulnerabilities reported, but the wiki page explains on how to report a vulnerability and how to report anonymously if you do not want the credit for it.
coding_standards_enforced_justification: SONAR compile time and Static Reporting tools enforce coding styles.
build_standard_variables_justification: AAF is written in Java, "run everywhere" on JVM.
build_preserve_debug_justification:
The application does not create native binaries.
All build info generated by Maven are stored as Jenkins Outputs for Job.
build_non_recursive_justification: AAF deliberately and specifically has no cross dependencies for artifacts.
build_repeatable_justification:
The application does not create native binaries.
AAF jars are always generated exactly the same way, with the same results, per source code set.
installation_standard_variables_justific: The compiled docker images and jar files can be installed/used as the user sees fit. Both run on JVM or docker. So there is no reason to selecting locations etc.
installation_development_quick_justifica:
All the components require only java and maven to begin with for a developer to quickly install and test it.  

Even for deployment using OOM and the right amount of resources, we can deploy the full AAI/ONAP suite in less than a day. The steps are documented in
https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/oom.git/docs/oom_quickstart_guide.html
external_dependencies_justification: External dependencies are controlled using the pom file, which can be found in the root folder for the project, https://gerrit.onap.org/r/gitweb?p=aaf/authz.git;a=tree
dependency_monitoring_justification: NexusIQ sonar scan is run on all the projects on a weekly basis
updateable_reused_components_justificati: External components are maintained through Maven. The user can get a list of all included components using the maven dependency tree and can update or reuse as they see fit
interfaces_current_justification: We avoid depending on deprecated/obsolete functions.
automated_integration_testing_justificat: Automatic test suites are run every time before  merging the code. The code check in cannot pass with out jenkins posting a +1 on the review.
regression_tests_added50_justification: When regressions occur, we add tests for them.
test_statement_coverage80_justification:
We use sonar to measure the code coverage. 
https://sonar.onap.org/about
test_policy_mandated_justification:
Contributing guide lines for development is recorded in
https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies
implement_secure_design_justification: AAF and CADI are designed to help applications meet Secure Principles, using best available Cryptography and practices (i.e. HTTP/S, TLS 1.1+, Certificates, etc)
input_validation_justification: AAF/CADI always requires both Authentication, and Authorization.  That is actually the purpose of this software to enable Apps to also always require Authentication and Authorization in a Fine-grained manner.
crypto_algorithm_agility_justification: Algorithms are provided by Java, which are constantly being updated.  Often, a simple upgrade to a later JDK is all that is required.
crypto_credential_agility_justification: AAF's CADI framework provides the ability to encrypt all passwords from Config Files, access to JKS/P12 files, etc.  No clear text passwords are allowed within the configuration.
signed_releases_justification: All release artifacts are signed by the Linux Foundation prior to release.
version_tags_signed_justification: All releases (which are tagged major/minor/patch) are signed by Linux Foundation.
contributors_unassociated_justification:
ONAP requires a committer other than the submitter to review each proposed modification.
https://wiki.onap.org/display/DW/Development+Procedures+and+Policies
copyright_per_file_justification: A standard Copyright header is required by ONAP/Linux Foundation, and cannot pass Maven Compilation without these headers.
license_per_file_justification: A standard License header is required by ONAP/Linux Foundation, and cannot pass Maven Compilation without these headers.
two_person_review_justification: ONAP Gerrit requires all reviews require +1 review by another member.
assurance_case_justification:
AAF/CADI is itself a security framework for Authentication and Authorization .  What it does is all documented in the initial docs.

https://onap.readthedocs.io/en/latest/submodules/aaf/authz.git/docs/index.html
maintained_justification: The original project lead retired, dropped out of ONAP, and this project (AAF) subsequently went fallow. No one else has pulled it together again, and AAF is one of the projects within ONAP that has moved to "unmaintained" stage. Other mechanisms have been deployed as replacements for AAF. This is unfortunate, as when it was active AAF did a good job in earning a badge and *explaining* why it had earned a badge.
